    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-02-01T09:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-02-01T09:00:00-05:00" n="183"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d183">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/3800: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Geneva (<persName corresp="#p_GPB1" type="from"
                            >Gilbert</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-02-01T15:00:00+01:00"
                            >February 1, 1932—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received February 1—11:23 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>65. 1. There have been persistent rumors here of a declaration of war on the part
                    of China.</p>
                <p>2. The Secretary General and Council members have impressed on <pb facs="0274"
                        n="170" xml:id="pg_170"/>
                    <persName corresp="#p_YWW1">Yen</persName> the extreme disadvantage in which
                    China would be placed should she take such a step particularly in the face of
                    her recent appeal under article 15 of the Covenant (see article 12 of the
                    Covenant, paragraph 1) and the consequent great tactical advantage under the
                    provisions of the Covenant which a declaration of war by China would give
                    Japan.</p>
                <p>3. I learn that <persName corresp="#p_YWW1">Yen</persName> while asserting that
                    these rumors are entirely unfounded and that China has no intention whatsoever
                    of declaring war has nevertheless telegraphed his Government in the strongest
                    terms pointing out the danger of any such a movement.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_GPB1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Gilbert</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
